<span class="type">Solution</span> <span class="acro">MM.C32</span> <span class="contributor"><a knowl="./knowls/contributor.chrisblack.knowl">Chris Black</a></span>
</h5>$A^{2} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 4 &amp; 0\\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 9\end{bmatrix}$,
$A^{3} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 8 &amp; 0\\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 27\end{bmatrix}$, and
$A^{4} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 16 &amp; 0\\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 81\end{bmatrix}$.
The pattern emerges, and we see that
$A^{n} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 2^n &amp; 0\\ 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 3^n\end{bmatrix}$.
